95, PMID:25830295]\ncomment: This term was obsoleted because it represents the same process as GO:0042784.\nsynonym: \"suppression of complement activation by another organism\" BROAD []\nproperty_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/26389\" xsd:anyURI\nis_obsolete: true\nreplaced_by: GO:0042784\ncreated_by: pg\ncreation_date: 2023-11-22T15:22:34Z\n\n[Term]\nid: GO:0141115\nname: symbiont-mediated suppression of host complement activation by inactivation of complement proteins\nnamespace: biological_process\ndef: \"A process by which a symbiont disrupts or prematurely activates host complement so that its microbial-destroying activities fail.\" [PMID:24312361, PMID:34305859]\nsynonym: \"suppression of complement activation by another organism by inactivation of complement proteins\" BROAD []\nis_a: GO:0042784 ! symbiont-mediated suppression of host complement activation\nproperty_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/26389\" xsd:anyURI\ncreated_by: pg\ncreation_date: 2023-11-22T15:32:58Z\n\n[Term]\nid: GO:0141116\nname: symbiont-mediated suppression of host complement activation by complement sequestering\nnamespace: biological_process\ndef: \"A process by which a symbiont prevents host complement activation by sequestering it away from its surface.\" [PMID:18323455]\nsynonym: \"suppression of complement activation by another organism by complement sequestering\" BROAD []\nis_a: GO:0042784 ! symbiont-mediated suppression of host complement activation\nproperty_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/26389\" xsd:anyURI\ncreated_by: pg\ncreation_date: 2023-11-22T15:34:16Z\n\n[Term]\nid: GO:0141117\nname: symbiont-mediated suppression of host complement activation by recruitment of complement control protein\nnamespace: biological_process\ndef: \"A process by which a symbiont prevents the activation of host complement by binding a soluble complement control protein (CCP) of the host and recruiting it to the microbe surface. The normal role of CCPs is to prevent complement activation on 'self' cellular targets. When soluble CCPs are recuited to the surface of a microbe, the complement fails to activate.\" [PMID:17513779, PMID:22540535, PMID:24129254, PMID:27304426]\nsynonym: \"suppression of complement activation by another organism by recruitment of complement control protein\" BROAD []\nsynonym: \"suppression of complement activation by another organism by recuitement of complement control protein\" EXACT []\nis_a: GO:0042784 ! symbiont-mediated suppression of host complement activation\nproperty_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/26389\" xsd:anyURI\ncreated_by: pg\ncreation_date: 2023-11-22T15:35:52Z\n\n[Term]\nid: GO:0141127\nname: symbiont-mediated perturbation of host Rab small GTPase signal transduction\nnamespace: biological_process\ndef: \"A process in which a symbiont alters a Rab protein family-mediated signal transduction pathway in its host organism. The host is defined as the larger of the organisms involved in a symbiotic interaction.\" [PMID:24251537, PMID:30181274, PMID:30893609]\nsynonym: \"modulation by symbiont of host Rab protein mediated signal transduction\" EXACT []\nsynonym: \"modulation by symbiont of host Rab protein signal transduction\" EXACT []\nsynonym: \"modulation by symbiont of host Rab protein-mediated signal transduction\" EXACT []\nsynonym: \"modulation of host Rab protein signal transduction by symbiont\" EXACT []\nsynonym: \"modulation of host Rab protein signaling by symbiont\" EXACT []\nsynonym: \"modulation of host Rab protein signalling by symbiont\" EXACT []\nsynonym: \"perturbation of host Rab protein signal transduction\" EXACT []\nsynonym: \"symbiont-mediated perturbation of host Rab protein signal transduction\" EXACT []\nis_a: GO:0044082 ! symbiont-mediated perturbation of host small GTPase-mediated signal transduction\nintersection_of: GO:0044003 ! symbiont-mediated perturbation of host process\nintersection_of: regulates_in_another_organism GO:0032482 ! Rab protein signal transduction\nproperty_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/26637\" xsd:anyURI\ncreated_by: pg\ncreation_date: 2023-12-13T15:10:26Z\n\n[Term]\nid: GO:0141128\nname: symbiont-mediated non-specific activation of host T-cells\nnamespace: biological_process\ndef: \"A process by which a symbiont superantigen elicits a strong immune response by activating a large number of T cells in a non-specific manner. Unlike conventional antigens, which activate T cells by interacting with specific receptors on the surface of these cells, superantigens can stimulate T cells by binding to regions outside the antigen-binding site. Superantigens can activate a large proportion of T cells, leading to an exaggerated immune response. This excessive activation can result in the release of a large amount of cytokines such as tumor necrosis factor and interleukin-2. The massive cytokine release can lead to an acute toxic shock, causing symptoms such as fever and organ damage.\" [PMID:12679262, PMID:17427250, PMID:28880920]\nsynonym: \"symbiont-mediated non-specific T-cell activation in host\" EXACT []\nsynonym: \"symbiont-mediated nonspecific activation of host T-cells\" EXACT []\nis_a: GO:0052553 ! symbiont-mediated perturbation of host immune response\nproperty_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/26638\" xsd:anyURI\ncreated_by: pg\ncreation_date: 2023-12-14T07:58:16Z\n\n[Term]\nid: GO:0141129\nname: symbiont-mediated suppression of host signal transduction pathway via antagonism of host cell surface receptor\nnamespace: biological_process\ndef: \"A process by which a symbiont alters or subverts a host cell surface receptor-mediated signal transduction pathway by binding to and inhibiting the receptor of the pathway. The host is defined as the larger of the organisms involved in a symbiotic interaction.\" [PMID:10221874, PMID:22714643]\nsynonym: \"symbiont-mediated perturbation of host signal transduction pathway via antagonism of host cell surface receptor\" BROAD []\nis_a: GO:0052029 ! symbiont-mediated suppression of host signal transduction pathway\nproperty_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/26310\" xsd:anyURI\ncreated_by: pg\ncreation_date: 2023-12-14T12:16:15Z\n\n[Term]\nid: GO:0141130\nname: symbiont-mediated inactivation of host ribosome\nnamespace: biological_process\ndef: \"A process in which a symbiont inhibits or disrupts translation of mRNA into protein in its host by inactivating its ribosomes.\" [PMID:1324134]\nsynonym: \"symbiont-mediated host ribosome inactivation\" EXACT []\nis_a: GO:0039604 ! symbiont-mediated suppression of host translation\nproperty_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/26184\" xsd:anyURI\ncreated_by: pg\ncreation_date: 2023-12-14T12:22:56Z\n\n[Term]\nid: GO:0141134\nname: symbiont-mediated activation of host signal transduction pathway via agonism of host cell surface receptor\nnamespace: biological_process\ndef: \"A process in which a symbiont subverts a signal transduction pathway in the host organism by binding to and enhancing the activation of the receptor of the pathway. The host is defined as the larger of the organisms involved in a symbiotic interaction.\" [PMID:10221874, PMID:18563600]\nsynonym: \"symbiont-mediated perturbation of host signal transduction pathway via antagonism of host cell surface receptor\" BROAD []\nis_a: GO:0052028 ! symbiont-mediated activation of host signal transduction pathway\nproperty_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/26310\" xsd:anyURI\ncreated_by: pg\ncreation_date: 2023-12-20T14:49:23Z\n\n[Term]\nid: GO:0141135\nname: symbiont-mediated suppression of host chemokine signal transduction pathway\nnamespace: biological_process\ndef: \"A process in which a symbiont interferes with, inhibits or disrupts a chemokine signaling pathway, a G protein-coupled receptor signal transduction pathway activated by a chemokine. The host is defined as the larger of the organisms involved in a symbiotic interaction.\" [PMID:16581912]\nis_a: GO:0075120 ! symbiont-mediated suppression of host G protein-coupled receptor signal transduction\nintersection_of: GO:0044003 ! symbiont-mediated perturbation of host process\nintersection_of: negatively_regulates_in_another_organism GO:0070098 ! chemokine-mediated signaling pathway\nproperty_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/26683\" xsd:anyURI\ncreated_by: pg\ncreation_date: 2023-12-20T15:40:32Z\n\n[Term]\nid: GO:0141139\nname: symbiont-mediated disruption of host mucosa\nnamespace: biological_process\ndef: \"The disruption of the host mucosa by a symbiont, leading to damage or temporary subversion of that tissue. The mucosa is a membrane that lines various cavities in the body of an organism and covers the surface of internal organs.\" [PMID:22520462, PMID:28598765, PMID:28764997]\nis_a: GO:0141146 ! symbiont-mediated disruption of host tissue\nproperty_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/26745\" xsd:anyURI\ncreated_by: pg\ncreation_date: 2024-01-16T09:44:42Z\n\n[Term]\nid: GO:0141140\nname: symbiont-mediated suppression of host immunoglobulin-mediated immune response\nnamespace: biological_process\ndef: \"A process in which a symbiont interferes with, inhibits or disrupts the normal execution of the immunoglobulin-mediated immune response of the host organism. One common mechanism by which this happens is the direct inhibition of immunoglobulin activity, by direct binding or modification. The host is defined as the larger of the organisms involved in a symbiotic interaction.\" [PMID:18426869, PMID:22256861, PMID:24753590]\nsynonym: \"symbiont-mediated suppression of host immunoglobulin activity\" RELATED []\nis_a: GO:0052562 ! symbiont-mediated suppression of host immune response\nproperty_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/26740\" xsd:anyURI\ncreated_by: pg\ncreation_date: 2024-01-16T09:55:22Z\n\n[Term]\nid: GO:0141141\nname: symbiont-mediated evasion of recognition by host pattern recognition receptor\nnamespace: biological_process\ndef: \"A process by which a symbiont avoids recognition by host's innate immune response by altering or concealing a conserved molecule recognized by the host's cell surface and intracellular pattern recognition receptors, including Toll-like and NOD-like receptors. The host is defined as the larger of the organisms involved in a symbiotic interaction.\" [PMID:17215377, PMID:26502908, PMID:29101229]\ncomment: Note that this term should be used when the symbiont in cases where the symbiont modifies its own molecules (proteins, DNA, RNA, lipids) to avoid recognition by the host. In cases where the symbiont  directly inhibits a component of a host cytoplasmic receptor signaling pathway, consider annotating to evasion of symbiont recognition by host pattern recognition receptor ; GO:0039537.\nsynonym: \"evasion of symbiont recognition by host pattern recognition receptor\" EXACT []\nis_a: GO:0141043 ! symbiont-mediated evasion of host innate immune response\nproperty_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/26743\" xsd:anyURI\nproperty_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/27250\" xsd:anyURI\ncreated_by: pg\ncreation_date: 2024-01-16T10:00:30Z\n\n[Term]\nid: GO:0141142\nname: symbiont-mediated migration across host tissue barrier\nnamespace: biological_process\ndef: \"A process in which a symbiont moves across a tissue barrier of the host to transports itself across an extracellular cellular matrix barrier or between the cells of a tissue. This involves the temporary or permanent breaching of the tissue barrier.\" [PMID:19820089, PMID:20188700, PMID:26681776, PMID:29120408]\nis_a: GO:0044001 ! migration in host\nproperty_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/26813\" xsd:anyURI\ncreated_by: pg\ncreation_date: 2024-01-17T15:32:41Z\n\n[Term]\nid: GO:0141143\nname: obsolete symbiont-mediated disruption of host cell adhesion to extracellular matrix\nnamespace: biological_process\ndef: \"OBSOLETE. A process in which a symbiont alters or subverts cell adhesion to the extracellular matrix in its host. The host is defined as the larger of the organisms involved in a symbiotic interaction.\" [PMID:22534208, PMID:30345086]\ncomment: This term was obsoleted because it was created by mistake.\nsynonym: \"disruption by symbiont of host cell adhesion to extracellular matrix\" EXACT []\nproperty_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/25172\" xsd:anyURI\nis_obsolete: true\nreplaced_by: GO:0141146\ncreated_by: pg\ncreation_date: 2024-01-17T15:47:43Z\n\n[Term]\nid: GO:0141144\nname: symbiont-mediated disruption of host neutrophil extracellular traps\nnamespace: biological_process\ndef: \"A process in which a symbiont damages or impairs host neutrophil extracellular traps. The host is defined as the larger of the organisms involved in a symbiotic interaction.\" [PMID:16488875, PMID:21231972, PMID:25605868]\nsynonym: \"symbiont-mediated perturbation of host neutrophil extracellular traps\" EXACT []\nis_a: GO:0052008 ! symbiont-mediated disruption of host cellular anatomical structure\nproperty_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/26811\" xsd:anyURI\ncreated_by: pg\ncreation_date: 2024-01-24T06:22:48Z\n\n[Term]\nid: GO:0141145\nname: symbiont-mediated suppression of host neutrophil extracellular trap formation\nnamespace: biological_process\ndef: \"A process in which a symbiont inhibits or disrupts the formation of neutrophil extracellular traps by the host cell. The host is defined as the larger of the organisms involved in a symbiotic interaction.\" [PMID:30038902, PMID:34108482]\nsynonym: \"symbiont-mediated perturbation of host neutrophil extracellular trap formation\" RELATED []\nsynonym: \"symbiont-mediated suppression of host neutrophil extracellular traps formation\" EXACT []\nis_a: GO:0052031 ! symbiont-mediated perturbation of host defense response\nintersection_of: GO:0044003 ! symbiont-mediated perturbation of host process\nintersection_of: negatively_regulates_in_another_organism GO:0140645 ! neutrophil extracellular trap formation\nproperty_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/26811\" xsd:anyURI\ncreated_by: pg\ncreation_date: 2024-01-24T06:32:59Z\n\n[Term]\nid: GO:0141146\nname: symbiont-mediated disruption of host tissue\nnamespace: biological_process\ndef: \"The process in which an organism effects a change that impairs the structure or function of a host tissue. This can occur via the disruption of the extracellular matrix, or the detachment of cells from the extracellular matrix, or the dissociation of the cells composing that tissue. The host is defined as the larger of the organisms involved in a symbiotic interaction.\" [PMID:11982763, PMID:14651638, PMID:26355030]\nsynonym: \"cytopathogenic effect\" RELATED []\nis_a: GO:0052111 ! symbiont-mediated disruption of host anatomical structure\nproperty_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/26814\" xsd:anyURI\ncreated_by: pg\ncreation_date: 2024-01-24T15:36:58Z\n\n[Term]\nid: GO:0141154\nname: symbiont-mediated suppression of host-directed shutoff of host translation\nnamespace: biological_process\ndef: \"A process in which a symbiont inhibits or disrupts the host shutoff of host translation, a host response that prevents mRNA in the cell to be translated, to prevent the symbiont from expressing its genes. The host is defined as the larger of the organisms involved in a symbiotic interaction.\" [PMID:20563710, PMID:21622569]\nis_a: GO:0044414 ! symbiont-mediated suppression of host defenses\nproperty_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/26918\" xsd:anyURI\ncreated_by: pg\ncreation_date: 2024-01-31T14:53:32Z\n\n[Term]\nid: GO:0141155\nname: symbiont-mediated suppression of host translation elongation\nnamespace: biological_process\ndef: \"A process in which a symbiont inhibits or disrupts the translation elongation of host mRNA into protein, for example by directly inhibiting elongation factors. The host is defined as the larger of the organisms involved in a symbiotic interaction.\" [PMID:10657208, PMID:18281405, PMID:18448518]\nis_a: GO:0039656 ! symbiont-mediated perturbation of host gene expression\nintersection_of: GO:0044003 ! symbiont-mediated perturbation of host process\nintersection_of: negatively_regulates_in_another_organism GO:0006414 ! translational elongation\nproperty_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/26918\" xsd:anyURI\ncreated_by: pg\ncreation_date: 2024-01-31T15:24:57Z\n\n[Term]\nid: GO:0141157\nname: symbiont-mediated suppression of host exocytosis\nnamespace: biological_process\ndef: \"A process in which a symbiont inhibits or disrupts the normal execution of  host exocytosis. The host is defined as the larger of the organisms involved in a symbiotic interaction.\" [PMID:17185412]\nintersection_of: GO:0044003 ! symbiont-mediated perturbation of host process\nintersection_of: negatively_regulates_in_another_organism GO:0006887 ! exocytosis\nproperty_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/26985\" xsd:anyURI\ncreated_by: pg\ncreation_date: 2024-02-07T15:18:55Z\n\n[Term]\nid: GO:0141158\nname: symbiont-mediated suppression of host phagosome maturation\nnamespace: biological_process\ndef: \"A process in which a symbiont inhibits or disrupts the normal maturation of host phagosomes. The host is defined as the larger of the organisms involved in a symbiotic interaction.\" [PMID:21501366, PMID:30181274, PMID:30733336, PMID:30937925]\nintersection_of: GO:0044003 ! symbiont-mediated perturbation of host process\nintersection_of: negatively_regulates_in_another_organism GO:0090382 ! phagosome maturation\nproperty_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/26987\" xsd:anyURI\ncreated_by: pg\ncreation_date: 2024-02-07T16:39:43Z\n\n[Term]\nid: GO:0141159\nname: symbiont-mediated suppression of host phagosome acidification\nnamespace: biological_process\ndef: \"A process in which a symbiont inhibits or disrupts the normal acidification of host phagosomes. Mechanisms by which a symbiont prevents host phagosome acidification include the inhibitition of host V-ATPase, the proton pump that acidifies the phagosome, or disruption of the phagosome membrane by pore-forming toxin. The host is defined as the larger of the organisms involved in a symbiotic interaction.\" [PMID:20333253, PMID:22087003, PMID:33505976]\nis_a: GO:0052031 ! symbiont-mediated perturbation of host defense response\nintersection_of: GO:0044003 ! symbiont-mediated perturbation of host process\nintersection_of: negatively_regulates_in_another_organism GO:0090383 ! phagosome acidification\nproperty_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/26987\" xsd:anyURI\ncreated_by: pg\ncreation_date: 2024-02-07T16:39:57Z\n\n[Term]\nid: GO:0141160\nname: symbiont-mediated disruption of host phagosome\nnamespace: biological_process\ndef: \"The process in which an organism effects a change that impairs the structure or function of host phagosomes.\" [PMID:15487949, PMID:21412437, PMID:30057173]\nis_a: GO:0052008 ! symbiont-mediated disruption of host cellular anatomical structure\nproperty_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/26987\" xsd:anyURI\ncreated_by: pg\ncreation_date: 2024-02-07T16:47:35Z\n\n[Term]\nid: GO:0141171\nname: symbiont-mediated perturbation of host membrane\nnamespace: biological_process\ndef: \"The process in which a symbiont effects a change that impairs the structure or function of a host membrane. The host is defined as the larger of the organisms involved in a symbiotic interaction.\" [PMID:14688136, PMID:17043230, PMID:28855258]\nsynonym: \"symbiont-mediated disruption of host membrane\" NARROW []\nis_a: GO:0052008 ! symbiont-mediated disruption of host cellular anatomical structure\nproperty_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/27130\" xsd:anyURI\ncreated_by: pg\ncreation_date: 2024-02-22T16:03:28Z\n\n[Term]\nid: GO:0141173\nname: symbiont-mediated suppression of host pro-inflammatory cytokine signaling\nnamespace: biological_process\ndef: \"A process by which a symbiont inhibits or disrupts pro-inflammatory cytokine signaling in the host organism, either by disruption of production, sequesteration, or destruction of at least one component of the signaling pathway. Pro-inflammatory cytokines include: IL-1, IL-12, IL-18, TNF, IFN-gamma, and GM-CSF. The host is defined as the larger of the organisms involved in a symbiotic interaction.\" [PMID:20008527, PMID:24508400, PMID:32117813]\nsynonym: \"negative regulation by symbiont of host pro-inflammatory cytokine production\" EXACT []\nsynonym: \"suppression by symbiont of host pro-inflammatory cytokine production\" EXACT []\nsynonym: \"suppression by symbiont of host pro-inflammatory cytokine secretion\" RELATED []\nsynonym: \"symbiont-mediated degradation of host pro-inflammatory cytokine\" NARROW []\nsynonym: \"symbiont-mediated sequestering of host pro-inflammatory cytokine\" RELATED []\nsynonym: \"symbiont-mediated suppression of host pro-inflammatory cytokine production\" RELATED []\nis_a: GO:0075109 ! symbiont-mediated perturbation of host receptor-mediated signal transduction\nproperty_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/27129\" xsd:anyURI\ncreated_by: pg\ncreation_date: 2024-02-22T16:33:40Z\n\n[Term]\nid: GO:0141174\nname: symbiont-mediated suppression of host anti-inflammatory cytokine signaling\nnamespace: biological_process\ndef: \"A process by which a symbiont inhibits or disrupts anti-inflammatory cytokine signaling in the host organism, either by disruption of production, sequesteration, or destruction of at least one component of the signaling pathway.  Anti-inflammatory cytokines include: interleukin (IL)-1, IL-4, IL-6, IL-10, IL-11, and IL-13. The host is defined as the larger of the organisms involved in a symbiotic interaction.\" [PMID:19168731, PMID:29720526, PMID:32754056]\nsynonym: \"negative regulation by symbiont of host anti-inflammatory cytokine production\" EXACT []\nsynonym: \"suppression by symbiont of host anti-inflammatory cytokine production\" EXACT []\nsynonym: \"suppression by symbiont of host anti-inflammatory cytokine secretion\" RELATED []\nsynonym: \"symbiont-mediated degradation of host anti-inflammatory cytokine\" NARROW []\nsynonym: \"symbiont-mediated sequestering of host anti-inflammatory cytokine\" RELATED []\nsynonym: \"symbiont-mediated suppression of host anti-inflammatory cytokine production\" RELATED []\nis_a: GO:0075109 ! symbiont-mediated perturbation of host receptor-mediated signal transduction\nproperty_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/27129\" xsd:anyURI\ncreated_by: pg\ncreation_date: 2024-02-22T16:35:54Z\n\n[Term]\nid: GO:0141177\nname: symbiont-mediated evasion of recognition by host innate immune effector\nnamespace: biological_process\ndef: \"A process by which a symbiont mitigates the effects of recognition by a host innate immune effector. Effectors have a direct activity against a symbiont and include complement, antimicrobial peptides, and bacterial restriction enzymes. The host is defined as the larger of the organisms involved in a symbiotic interaction.\" [PMID:19208801, PMID:33330873]\nsynonym: \"evasion of symbiont recognition by host innate immune effector\" EXACT []\nis_a: GO:0141043 ! symbiont-mediated evasion of host innate immune response\nproperty_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/27250\" xsd:anyURI\ncreated_by: pg\ncreation_date: 2024-03-12T13:23:48Z\n\n[Term]\nid: GO:0141178\nname: symbiont-mediated evasion of recognition by host complement\nnamespace: biological_process\ndef: \"A process by which a symbiont avoids the effects of recognition by host  complement by altering molecules on the symbiont surface. The host is defined as the larger of the organisms involved in a symbiotic interaction.\" [PMID:22825444, PMID:25537831, PMID:34887398]\nsynonym: \"symbiont-mediated evasion of host complement\" EXACT []\nis_a: GO:0141177 ! symbiont-mediated evasion of recognition by host innate immune effector\nproperty_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/27250\" xsd:anyURI\ncreated_by: pg\ncreation_date: 2024-03-12T14:01:12Z\n\n[Term]\nid: GO:0141179\nname: symbiont-mediated evasion of recognition by host antimicrobial peptide\nnamespace: biological_process\ndef: \"A process by which a symbiont avoids the effects of recognition by a host  antimicrobial peptide by altering molecules on the symbiont surface. The host is defined as the larger of the organisms involved in a symbiotic interaction.\" [PMID:11401964, PMID:22966934, PMID:25537831]\nis_a: GO:0141177 ! symbiont-mediated evasion of recognition by host innate immune effector\nproperty_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/27250\" xsd:anyURI\ncreated_by: pg\ncreation_date: 2024-03-12T14:09:42Z\n\n[Term]\nid: GO:0141184\nname: symbiont-mediated activation of host anti-inflammatory cytokine signaling\nnamespace: biological_process\ndef: \"A process in which a symbiont subverts an anti-inflammatory cytokine signaling pathway in the host organism by initiating, promoting, or enhancing its activation.\" [PMID:23284742, PMID:27437422, PMID:29924996]\nis_a: GO:0052028 ! symbiont-mediated activation of host signal transduction pathway\nproperty_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/27129\" xsd:anyURI\ncreated_by: pg\ncreation_date: 2024-03-19T13:30:47Z\n\n[Term]\nid: GO:0141203\nname: symbiont-mediated suppression of host complement activation by activation of host proteases\nnamespace: biological_process\ndef: \"A process by which a symbiont prevents host complement activation by recruiting host proteases, destroying the complement before it has its effect on the symbiont.\" [PMID:15792635, PMID:26945067, PMID:34305859]\nsynonym: \"symbiont-mediated suppression of host complement activation by recruitment of host proteases\" NARROW []\nis_a: GO:0042784 ! symbiont-mediated suppression of host complement activation\nproperty_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/27788\" xsd:anyURI\ncreated_by: pg\ncreation_date: 2024-04-30T13:17:35Z\n\n[Term]\nid: GO:0141213\nname: symbiont-mediated generation of symbiont replication vacuole\nnamespace: biological_process\ndef: \"A process in which a symbiont alters or subverts vacuole organization in its host organism to form a protected environment in which it can replicate. The host is defined as the larger of the organisms involved in a symbiotic interaction.\" [PMID:21822290, PMID:23186105, PMID:30893609]\nis_a: GO:0044075 ! symbiont-mediated perturbation of host vacuole organization\nproperty_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/28420\" xsd:anyURI\ncreated_by: pg\ncreation_date: 2024-07-09T12:42:21Z\n\n[Term]\nid: GO:1903652\nname: obsolete modulation by virus of host cytoplasmic transport\nnamespace: biological_process\ndef: \"OBSOLETE. Modulation by an infecting virus of host cytoplasmic transport.\" [GO_REF:0000063, GOC:TermGenie, PMID:25049409]\ncomment: This te