{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_70","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/bash -lc \"sed -n '1,220p' ISSUE_COMMENTS.md && sed -n '1,260p' PR_COMMENTS.md\"","aggregated_output":"Created `GO:7770070 symbiont-mediated suppression of host platelet aggregation`.\n\nThe term follows the existing symbiont-mediated suppression pattern and is supported by PMID:2401564 and PMID:8486945. Changes committed in PR #<NN>.\n## Summary\n\nAdded `GO:7770070 symbiont-mediated suppression of host platelet aggregation` in response to issue #31936.\n\nThe new term follows the existing `symbiont-mediated suppression of host process` design pattern:\n\n* genus: `GO:0044003 symbiont-mediated perturbation of host process`\n* differentia: `negatively_regulates_in_another_organism GO:0070527 platelet aggregation`\n\nThis fills the symbiont-mediated counterpart to the existing venom-mediated term `GO:0044477 venom-mediated suppression of platelet aggregation`. It also addresses the gap noted on the obsolete term `GO:0035893 obsolete suppression of platelet aggregation in another organism`, which was obsoleted because it did not distinguish symbiont- from venom-mediated processes.\n\n## Biological Rationale\n\nReference checks identified two directly relevant examples:\n\n* PMID:2401564: Yersinia pestis YopM-containing supernatant proteins inhibited thrombin- or ristocetin-induced platelet aggregation.\n* PMID:8486945: Streptococcal exopolysaccharides inhibited platelet binding and aggregation by streptococci.\n\nThese support a GO process in which a symbiont suppresses platelet aggregation in its host.\n\n## Validation\n\n* Pre-validation: `make -C src/ontology travis_build` passed before ontology edits.\n* Reference validation: `linkml-reference-validator validate text-file -r 'SUPPORT: (\\S+:\\S+) \"(.*)\"' -t 2 -R 1 RESEARCH.md` passed.\n* Post-edit validation: `make -C src/ontology travis_build` passed.\n\nNote: an optional `runoak` hierarchy display failed due a local Python dependency mismatch (`Format.JSON` versus `Format.JSONLD`), so hierarchy inspection was done using `obo-grep.pl` and existing term precedents instead.\n\n## Checklist\n\n* [x] PLAN: Issue context analyzed; title provided a clear NTR for a new term.\n* [x] PRE-VALIDATION: Current ontology validated before changes.\n* [x] RESEARCH: Background research performed and documented in `RESEARCH.md`.\n* [x] TERM-SEARCH: Existing GO terms and relevant imported CL platelet term checked.\n* [x] DESIGN-PATTERNS: Existing DOSDP and term precedents documented in `DESIGN_PATTERNS.md`.\n* [x] EDITS: New term created in `terms/` and checked into `src/ontology/go-edit.obo`.\n* [x] RELATIONSHIPS: Logical definition uses the established symbiont-mediated suppression pattern.\n* [x] SPECIALIZED-EDITS: N/A; no obsoletion, CHEBI, catalytic activity, mapping, or taxon constraint edit was needed.\n* [x] METADATA: New term includes namespace, definition provenance, term tracker link, `created_by`, and `creation_date`.\n* [x] AUTOMATED-VALIDATION: `make -C src/ontology travis_build` passed after changes.\n* [x] REFERENCE-VALIDATION: PMID support text validated against cached reference content.\n* [x] CHANGES-COMMITTED: Committed locally as `0b18821`.\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
